		<td><b>UncleSporky</b> [ Tue Dec 29, 2009 11:17 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Colino wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I've had some experience with basic Assembler before, are they very similar? I don't have to move (MOV) values between parts of memory to do a multiplication right?  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_lol.gif" alt=":lol:" title="Laughing" /></div>
<br />In a way, yes, you do.  There's no "multiply" command so you will have to calculate using adds and shifting bits, and it's likely you won't be able to fit all the numbers into the registers at once so you will have to copy data back and forth.
<br />
<br />Alternatively there are faster ways to do multiplication using lookup tables.
<br />
<br />It gets pretty complicated at times!  Like others, I recommend the NES 101 tutorial that takes you through a simple program which you can modify to see real results and what affects what.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


