	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Assembly isn't hard at all, once you understand how it works. I used to work with QBasic and Pascal before learning ASM, and I was confused as hell at first.
<br />
<br />What you have to understand is that every task is performed in very small bits, and since each instruction does so little you need a lot of them in order to complete a more complex task.
<br />
<br />The most confusing thing about ASM, to me at least, were the status flags. Being used to IF and WHILE structures, I simply couldn't understand how the branch instructions worked. Just keep in mind that certain operations change the flags according to the result of these operations, and that the branch instructions will branch or not depending on whether flags are set or clear. If you understand that you can replicate every program flow structure found in high-level languages without problems.
<br />
<br />ASM is really fun though, you will not regret learning it. You will have freedom like you never had in any other language, and will be able to make optimizations that are impossible with anything else. And you will learn a lot about computer architecture.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


